The paper presents a legged motion planning approach for quadrupedal locomotion over challenging terrain, which involves the use of lattice representation, body movement primitives, and footstep planning. These techniques are commonly used in the field of robotics (cs.RO) for motion planning and control. The paper also mentions the use of Anytime Repairing A* (ARA*) search, which is a popular search algorithm in artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of perception for terrain information, which is a common topic in computer vision (cs.CV) and systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper mentions the use of experimental trials to demonstrate the performance of the planning approach, which is a common practice in machine learning (cs.LG).
